  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="pb-16">
    <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-[14px]" style="background:var(--card); border:1px solid var(--border);">
      <div class="p-5" style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--bg);">
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold" style="color:var(--fg);">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-trigger w-full text-left flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5">
          <span class="text-sm font-medium" style="color:var(--fg);">What is CIDR notation?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4 shrink-0 transition-transform" style="color:var(--fg3);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color:var(--fg2);">
          CIDR (Classless Inter-Domain Routing) notation is a compact way to express an IP address range. It consists of an IP address followed by a slash and a prefix length, for example <code class="ic">192.168.1.0/24</code>. The prefix length indicates how many leading bits are the network portion. <code class="ic">/24</code> means the first 24 bits identify the network, leaving 8 bits for host addresses (256 total IPs). CIDR replaced the older Class A/B/C system and allows more efficient allocation of address space.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-trigger w-full text-left flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5">
          <span class="text-sm font-medium" style="color:var(--fg);">How do I calculate a subnet mask from a CIDR prefix?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4 shrink-0 transition-transform" style="color:var(--fg3);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color:var(--fg2);">
          Set the first N bits to 1, where N is the prefix length, in a 32-bit number. For <code class="ic">/24</code>: <code class="ic">11111111.11111111.11111111.00000000</code> = <code class="ic">255.255.255.0</code>. For <code class="ic">/16</code>: <code class="ic">255.255.0.0</code>. For <code class="ic">/8</code>: <code class="ic">255.0.0.0</code>. The wildcard mask is the bitwise inverse — for /24 that's <code class="ic">0.0.0.255</code>, useful in ACLs and firewall rules. This calculator shows both subnet and wildcard masks instantly.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-trigger w-full text-left flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5">
          <span class="text-sm font-medium" style="color:var(--fg);">What is the difference between IPv4 and IPv6 subnetting?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4 shrink-0 transition-transform" style="color:var(--fg3);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color:var(--fg2);">
          IPv4 uses 32-bit addresses (e.g. <code class="ic">192.168.1.0/24</code>) with prefix lengths from /0 to /32. It reserves one address for the network ID and one for broadcast, reducing usable hosts by 2. IPv6 uses 128-bit addresses (e.g. <code class="ic">2001:db8::/32</code>) with prefix lengths from /0 to /128. IPv6 has no broadcast address. Every address in the range is usable. IPv6 subnets are typically /64, giving each network 2⁶⁴ ≈ 18 quintillion addresses. ISPs typically assign /48 or /56 prefixes to customers.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-trigger w-full text-left flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5">
          <span class="text-sm font-medium" style="color:var(--fg);">How many hosts can a /24 subnet have?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4 shrink-0 transition-transform" style="color:var(--fg3);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color:var(--fg2);">
          A /24 subnet contains <strong style="color:var(--fg);">256 total IPs</strong> (2⁸ = 256). Two are reserved: the network address (e.g. <code class="ic">192.168.1.0</code>) and the broadcast address (e.g. <code class="ic">192.168.1.255</code>), leaving <strong style="color:var(--fg);">254 usable host addresses</strong>. Common subnet sizes: /30 = 2 usable, /29 = 6, /28 = 14, /27 = 30, /26 = 62, /25 = 126, /24 = 254, /23 = 510, /22 = 1022, /21 = 2046, /20 = 4094, /16 = 65,534.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item" style="border-bottom:none;">
        <button class="faq-trigger w-full text-left flex items-center justify-between gap-4 p-5">
          <span class="text-sm font-medium" style="color:var(--fg);">How do I plan subnets for an AWS VPC?</span>
          <svg class="faq-chevron w-4 h-4 shrink-0 transition-transform" style="color:var(--fg3);" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><polyline points="6 9 12 15 18 9"/></svg>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-5 pb-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color:var(--fg2);">
          Start with a <code class="ic">/16</code> VPC CIDR (e.g. <code class="ic">10.0.0.0/16</code>) and create three tiers: <strong style="color:#22c55e;">Public</strong> subnets for ALBs and NAT gateways, <strong style="color:#6366f1;">Private</strong> subnets for application servers and ECS tasks, and <strong style="color:#f59e0b;">Database</strong> subnets for RDS and ElastiCache. Replicate each tier across at least 2 Availability Zones for HA. A /16 split into /18s gives 4 subnets of 16,382 usable hosts each. Use the <strong style="color:var(--fg);">AWS VPC Subnet Planner</strong> above to generate CIDRs automatically.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

